SaraAriY~N *
A sailor: (S, M, K:) like SaArK: (S:) pl. SaraAriy~uwna: (S, M, K:) it has no broken pl.: (M:) or Sar~AriY~ should be [without tenween, imperfectly decl., and] mentioned in art. SrY; for it is pl. of Sur~aA='N, which is pl. of SaArK, which J has mentioned in art. SrY: AHát used to say that Sur~aA='N is a sing., like Hus~aAnN; but without sufficient authority: and J has regarded SaraAriY~ as a sing. in consequence of his finding it to have the same construction as a sing, in verses of Arabs;
whence he imagined the Y in it to be the relative Y, as is shown by his mentioning the word in this place. (IB.)

1 SaEuba * , (S, A, MA, Msb, K,) aor.
SaEuba , (A, K,) inf. n. SuEuwbapN; (S, MA, Msb, K;) and ↓ AstSEb;
(S, A, MA, Msb, K;) and ↓ ASEb, (IAar, K,) inf. n. A_iSoEaAbN; (IAar, TA;) It (a thing, Msb, or an affair, or event, S, MA, Msb, K) was, or became, SaEob, (S, A, &c.,) i. e. difficult, hard, hard to be done or accomplished, hard to be borne or endured, or distressing. (A, MA, K.) One says, Ealayohi AlA^amoru ↓ AstSEb, (S, MA, Msb,) like SaEuba, (S, Msb,) The affair, or event, was, or became, difficult, &c., to him. (MA.)
